# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: avl-tree
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] In computer science, an **AVL tree** (named after inventors **A**delson-**V**elsky and **L**andis) is a self-balancing binary search tree.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] In an AVL tree, the heights of the two child subtrees of any node differ by not more than one; if at any time they differ by more than one, rebalancing is done to restore this property.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Lookup, insertion, and deletion all take O(log *n*) time in both the average and worst cases, where n is the number of nodes in the tree prior to the operation.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Insertions and deletions may require the tree to be rebalanced by one or more tree rotations.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] The AVL tree is named after its two Soviet inventors, Georgy Adelson-Velsky and Evgenii Landis, who published it in their 1962 paper "An algorithm for the organization of information".
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] It is the first self-balancing binary search tree data structure to be invented.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] AVL trees are often compared with red–black trees because both support the same set of operations and take ${\text{O}}(\log n)$ time for the basic operations.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] For lookup-intensive applications, AVL trees are faster than red–black trees because they are more strictly balanced.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Similar to red–black trees, AVL trees are height-balanced.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Both are, in general, neither weight-balanced nor $\mu$ -balanced for any $\mu \leq {\tfrac {1}{2}}$ ; that is, sibling nodes can have hugely differing numbers of descendants.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] of its two child sub-trees rooted by node *X*.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] A node *X* with $\mathrm {BF} (X)<0$ is called "left-heavy", one with $\mathrm {BF} (X)>0$ is called "right-heavy", and one with $\mathrm {BF} (X)=0$ is sometimes simply called "balanced".
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Balance factors can be kept up-to-date by knowing the previous balance factors and the change in height – it is not necessary to know the absolute height.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] For holding the AVL balance information, two bits per node are sufficient.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Read-only operations of an AVL tree involve carrying out the same actions as would be carried out on an unbalanced binary search tree, but modifications have to observe and restore the height balance of the sub-trees.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Searching for a specific key in an AVL tree can be done the same way as that of any balanced or unbalanced binary search tree.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] In order for search to work effectively it has to employ a comparison function which establishes a total order (or at least a total preorder) on the set of keys.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] The number of comparisons required for successful search is limited by the height *h* and for unsuccessful search is very close to *h*, so both are in O(log *n*), where n is the number of nodes in the tree.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] As a read-only operation the traversal of an AVL tree functions the same way as on any other binary tree.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Exploring all *n* nodes of the tree visits each link exactly twice: one downward visit to enter the subtree rooted by that node, another visit upward to leave that node's subtree after having explored it.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Once a node has been found in an AVL tree, the *next* or *previous* node can be accessed in amortized constant time.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Since there are *n*−1 links in any tree, the amortized cost is 2×(*n*−1)/*n*, or approximately 2.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] When inserting a node into an AVL tree, you initially follow the same process as inserting into a Binary Search Tree.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] If the tree is empty, then the node is inserted as the root of the tree.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] If the tree is not empty, then we go down the root, and recursively go down the tree searching for the location to insert the new node.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] This traversal is guided by the comparison function.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] In this case, the node always replaces a NULL reference (left or right) of an external node in the tree i.e., the node is either made a left-child or a right-child of the external node.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] After this insertion, if a tree becomes unbalanced, only ancestors of the newly inserted node are unbalanced.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] This is because only those nodes have their sub-trees altered.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] So it is necessary to check each of the node's ancestors for consistency with the invariants of AVL trees: this is called "retracing".
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] This is achieved by considering the balance factor of each node.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Since with a single insertion the height of an AVL subtree cannot increase by more than one, the temporary balance factor of a node after an insertion will be in the range [–2,+2].
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] For each node checked, if the temporary balance factor remains in the range from –1 to +1 then only an update of the balance factor and no rotation is necessary.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] However, if the temporary balance factor is ±2, the subtree rooted at this node is AVL unbalanced, and a rotation is needed.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] With insertion as the code below shows, the adequate rotation immediately perfectly rebalances the tree.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] In figure 1, by inserting the new node Z as a child of node X the height of that subtree Z increases from 0 to 1.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] The height of the subtree rooted by Z has increased by 1.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] In order to update the balance factors of all nodes, first observe that all nodes requiring correction lie from child to parent along the path of the inserted leaf.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] If the above procedure is applied to nodes along this path, starting from the leaf, then every node in the tree will again have a balance factor of −1, 0, or 1.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] The retracing can stop if the balance factor becomes 0 implying that the height of that subtree remains unchanged.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] If the balance factor becomes ±1 then the height of the subtree increases by one and the retracing needs to continue.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] If the balance factor temporarily becomes ±2, this has to be repaired by an appropriate rotation after which the subtree has the same height as before (and its root the balance factor 0).
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] The time required is O(log *n*) for lookup, plus a maximum of O(log *n*) retracing levels (O(1) on average) on the way back to the root, so the operation can be completed in O(log *n*) time.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] The preliminary steps for deleting a node are the same as for a Binary search tree.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] There, the effective deletion of the subject node or the replacement node decreases the height of the corresponding child tree either from 1 to 0 or from 2 to 1, if that node had a child.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Starting at this subtree, it is necessary to check each of the ancestors for consistency with the invariants of AVL trees.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Since with a single deletion the height of an AVL subtree cannot decrease by more than one, the temporary balance factor of a node will be in the range from −2 to +2.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] If the balance factor remains in the range from −1 to +1 it can be adjusted in accord with the AVL rules.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] If it becomes ±2 then the subtree is unbalanced and needs to be rotated.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] The height of the subtree rooted by N has decreased by 1.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] The retracing can stop if the balance factor becomes ±1 (it must have been 0) meaning that the height of that subtree remains unchanged.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] If the balance factor becomes 0 (it must have been ±1) then the height of the subtree decreases by one and the retracing needs to continue.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] If the balance factor temporarily becomes ±2, this has to be repaired by an appropriate rotation.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] It depends on the balance factor of the sibling Z (the higher child tree in figure 2) whether the height of the subtree decreases by one –and the retracing needs to continue– or does not change (if Z has the balance factor 0) and the whole tree is in AVL-shape.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] In addition to the single-element insert, delete and lookup operations, several set operations have been defined on AVL trees: union, intersection and set difference.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Then fast *bulk* operations on insertions or deletions can be implemented based on these set functions.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] These set operations rely on two helper operations, *Split* and *Join*.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] With the new operations, the implementation of AVL trees can be more efficient and highly-parallelizable.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] The function *Join* on two AVL trees *t*1 and *t*2 and a key k will return a tree containing all elements in *t*1, *t*2 as well as k.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] It requires k to be greater than all keys in *t*1 and smaller than all keys in *t*2.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] If the two trees differ by height at most one, *Join* simply create a new node with left subtree *t*1, root k and right subtree *t*2.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Otherwise, suppose that *t*1 is higher than *t*2 for more than one (the other case is symmetric).
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] *Join* follows the right spine of *t*1 until a node c which is balanced with *t*2.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] At this point a new node with left child c, root k and right child *t*2 is created to replace c.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] The new node satisfies the AVL invariant, and its height is one greater than c.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] The increase in height can increase the height of its ancestors, possibly invalidating the AVL invariant of those nodes.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] This can be fixed either with a double rotation if invalid at the parent or a single left rotation if invalid higher in the tree, in both cases restoring the height for any further ancestor nodes.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] *Join* will therefore require at most two rotations.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] The cost of this function is the difference of the heights between the two input trees.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] To split an AVL tree into two smaller trees, those smaller than key k, and those greater than key k, first draw a path from the root by inserting k into the AVL.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] After this insertion, all values less than k will be found on the left of the path, and all values greater than k will be found on the right.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] By applying *Join*, all the subtrees on the left side are merged bottom-up using keys on the path as intermediate nodes from bottom to top to form the left tree, and the right part is asymmetric.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] The cost of *Split* is O(log *n*), order of the height of the tree.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] The union of two AVL trees *t*1 and *t*2 representing sets A and B, is an AVL *t* that represents *A* ∪ *B*.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] The algorithm for intersection or difference is similar, but requires the *Join2* helper routine that is the same as *Join* but without the middle key.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Based on the new functions for union, intersection or difference, either one key or multiple keys can be inserted to or deleted from the AVL tree.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Since *Split* calls *Join* but does not deal with the balancing criteria of AVL trees directly, such an implementation is usually called the "join-based" implementation.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] The complexity of each of union, intersection and difference is ${\text{O}}\left(m\log \left({n \over m}+1\right)\right)$ for AVL trees of sizes m and $n\;(\geq m)$ .
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] More importantly, since the recursive calls to union, intersection or difference are independent of each other, they can be executed in parallel with a parallel depth ${\text{O}}(\log m\log n)$ .
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] When $m=1$ , the join-based implementation has the same computational DAG as single-element insertion and deletion.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] If during a modifying operation the height difference between two child subtrees changes, this may, as long as it is < 2, be reflected by an adaption of the balance information at the parent.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] During insert and delete operations a (temporary) height difference of 2 may arise, which means that the parent subtree has to be "rebalanced".
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] The given repair tools are the so-called tree rotations, because they move the keys only "vertically", so that the ("horizontal") in-order sequence of the keys is fully preserved (which is essential for a binary-search tree).
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Let X be the node that has a (temporary) balance factor of −2 or +2.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Let Z be the child with the higher subtree (see figures 2 and 3).
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Note that both children are in AVL shape by induction hypothesis.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] In case of insertion this insertion has happened to one of Z's children in a way that Z's height has increased.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] In case of deletion this deletion has happened to the sibling t1 of Z in a way so that t1's height being already lower has decreased.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Thereby, the situations are denoted as *C B*, where *C* (= child direction) and *B* (= balance) come from the set { *Left*, *Right* } with *Right* := −*Left*.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] The balance violation of case *C* == *B* is repaired by a simple rotation `rotate_`(−*C*), whereas the case *C* != *B* is repaired by a double rotation `rotate_`*CB*.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] The cost of a rotation, either simple or double, is constant.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] In its upper half, node X has two child trees with a balance factor of +2.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Moreover, the inner child t23 of Z (i.e., left child when Z is right child, or right child when Z is left child) is not higher than its sibling t4.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] This can happen by a height increase of subtree t4 or by a height decrease of subtree t1.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] In the latter case, also the pale situation where t23 has the same height as t4 may occur.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] The result of the left rotation is shown in the lower half of the figure.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Three links (thick edges in figure 2) and two balance factors are to be updated.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] As the figure shows, before an insertion, the leaf layer was at level h+1, temporarily at level h+2 and after the rotation again at level h+1.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] In case of a deletion, the leaf layer was at level h+2, where it is again, when t23 and t4 were of same height.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Otherwise the leaf layer reaches level h+1, so that the height of the rotated tree decreases.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] In its upper third, node X has two child trees with a balance factor of +2.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] But unlike figure 2, the inner child Y of Z is higher than its sibling t4.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] This can happen by the insertion of Y itself or a height increase of one of its subtrees t2 or t3 (with the consequence that they are of different height) or by a height decrease of subtree t1.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] In the latter case, it may also occur that t2 and t3 are of the same height.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] The result of the first, the right, rotation is shown in the middle third of the figure.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] (With respect to the balance factors, this rotation is not of the same kind as the other AVL single rotations, because the height difference between Y and t4 is only 1.) The result of the final left rotation is shown in the lower third of the figure.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Five links (thick edges in figure 3) and three balance factors are to be updated.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] As the figure shows, before an insertion, the leaf layer was at level h+1, temporarily at level h+2 and after the double rotation again at level h+1.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] In case of a deletion, the leaf layer was at level h+2 and after the double rotation it is at level h+1, so that the height of the rotated tree decreases.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Both AVL trees and red–black (RB) trees are self-balancing binary search trees and they are related mathematically.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] Indeed, every AVL tree can be colored red–black, but there are RB trees which are not AVL balanced.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] For maintaining the AVL (or RB) tree's invariants, rotations play an important role.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] In the worst case, even without rotations, AVL or RB insertions or deletions require O(log *n*) inspections and/or updates to AVL balance factors (or RB colors).
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] RB insertions and deletions and AVL insertions require from zero to three tail-recursive rotations and run in amortized O(1) time, thus equally constant on average.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] AVL deletions requiring O(log *n*) rotations in the worst case are also O(1) on average.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] RB trees require storing one bit of information (the color) in each node, while AVL trees mostly use two bits for the balance factor, although, when stored at the children, one bit with meaning «lower than sibling» suffices.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] The bigger difference between the two data structures is their height limit.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] AVL trees are more rigidly balanced than RB trees with an asymptotic relation AVL/RB ≈0.720 of the maximal heights.
[src:avl-tree/avl-tree] For insertions and deletions, Ben Pfaff shows in 79 measurements a relation of AVL/RB between 0.677 and 1.077 with median ≈0.947 and geometric mean ≈0.910.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] In computer science, a **binary search tree** (**BST**), also called an **ordered** or **sorted binary tree**, is a rooted binary tree data structure with the key of each internal node being greater than all the keys in the respective node's left subtree and less than the ones in its right subtree.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] The time complexity of operations on the binary search tree is linear with respect to the height of the tree.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees allow binary search for fast lookup, addition, and removal of data items.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] Since the nodes in a BST are laid out so that each comparison skips about half of the remaining tree, the lookup performance is proportional to that of binary logarithm.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] BSTs were devised in the 1960s for the problem of efficient storage of labeled data and are attributed to Conway Berners-Lee and David Wheeler.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] The performance of a binary search tree is dependent on the order of insertion of the nodes into the tree since arbitrary insertions may lead to degeneracy; several variations of the binary search tree can be built with guaranteed worst-case performance.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] The basic operations include: search, traversal, insert and delete.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] BSTs with guaranteed worst-case complexities perform better than an unsorted array, which would require linear search time.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] The complexity analysis of BST shows that, on average, the insert, delete and search takes $\Theta (\log n)$ for n nodes.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] In the worst case, they degrade to that of a singly linked list: $O(n)$ .
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] To address the boundless increase of the tree height with arbitrary insertions and deletions, self-balancing variants of BSTs are introduced to bound the worst lookup complexity to that of the binary logarithm.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] AVL trees were the first self-balancing binary search trees, invented in 1962 by Georgy Adelson-Velsky and Evgenii Landis.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees can be used to implement abstract data types such as dynamic sets, lookup tables and priority queues, and used in sorting algorithms such as tree sort.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] The binary search tree algorithm was discovered independently by several researchers, including P.F.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] Windley, Andrew Donald Booth, Andrew Colin, Thomas N.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] The algorithm is attributed to Conway Berners-Lee and David Wheeler, who used it for storing labeled data in magnetic tapes in 1960.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] One of the earliest and popular binary search tree algorithm is that of Hibbard.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] The time complexity of a binary search tree increases boundlessly with the tree height if the nodes are inserted in an arbitrary order, therefore self-balancing binary search trees were introduced to bound the height of the tree to $O(\log n)$ .
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] Various **height-balanced** binary search trees were introduced to confine the tree height, such as AVL trees, Treaps, and red–black trees.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are also efficacious in sortings and search algorithms.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are also a fundamental data structure used in construction of abstract data structures such as sets, multisets, and associative arrays.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] Searching in a binary search tree for a specific key can be programmed recursively or iteratively.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] Searching begins by examining the root node.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] If the tree is nil, the key being searched for does not exist in the tree.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] Otherwise, if the key equals that of the root, the search is successful and the node is returned.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] If the key is less than that of the root, the search proceeds by examining the left subtree.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] Similarly, if the key is greater than that of the root, the search proceeds by examining the right subtree.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] This process is repeated until the key is found or the remaining subtree is ${\text{nil}}$ .
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] If the searched key is not found after a ${\text{nil}}$ subtree is reached, then the key is not present in the tree.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] The following pseudocode implements the BST search procedure through recursion.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] The recursive procedure continues until a ${\text{nil}}$ or the ${\text{key}}$ being searched for are encountered.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] The recursive version of the search can be "unrolled" into a while loop.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] On most machines, the iterative version is found to be more efficient.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] Since the search may proceed till some leaf node, the running time complexity of BST search is $O(h)$ where h is the height of the tree.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] However, the worst case for BST search is $O(n)$ where n is the total number of nodes in the BST, because an unbalanced BST may degenerate to a linked list.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] However, if the BST is height-balanced the height is $O(\log n)$ .
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] For certain operations, given a node ${\text{x}}$ , finding the successor or predecessor of ${\text{x}}$ is crucial.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] Assuming all the keys of a BST are distinct, the successor of a node ${\text{x}}$ in a BST is the node with the smallest key greater than ${\text{x}}$ 's key.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] On the other hand, the predecessor of a node ${\text{x}}$ in a BST is the node with the largest key smaller than ${\text{x}}$ 's key.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] The following pseudocode finds the successor and predecessor of a node ${\text{x}}$ in a BST.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] Operations such as finding a node in a BST whose key is the maximum or minimum are critical in certain operations, such as determining the successor and predecessor of nodes.
