[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] A BST can be traversed through three basic algorithms: inorder, preorder, and postorder tree walks.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] Following is a recursive implementation of the tree walks.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] Without rebalancing, insertions or deletions in a binary search tree may lead to degeneration, resulting in a height n of the tree (where n is number of items in a tree), so that the lookup performance is deteriorated to that of a linear search.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] Keeping the search tree balanced and height bounded by $O(\log n)$ is a key to the usefulness of the binary search tree.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] This can be achieved by "self-balancing" mechanisms during the updation operations to the tree designed to maintain the tree height to the binary logarithmic complexity.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] A tree is height-balanced if the heights of the left sub-tree and right sub-tree are guaranteed to be related by a constant factor.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] This property was introduced by the AVL tree and continued by the red–black tree.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] The heights of all the nodes on the path from the root to the modified leaf node have to be observed and possibly corrected on every insert and delete operation to the tree.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] In a weight-balanced tree, the criterion of a balanced tree is the number of leaves of the subtrees.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] The weights of the left and right subtrees differ at most by 1 .
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] However, the difference is bound by a ratio $\alpha$ of the weights, since a strong balance condition of 1 cannot be maintained with $O(\log n)$ rebalancing work during insert and delete operations.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] The $\alpha$ -weight-balanced trees gives an entire family of balance conditions, where each left and right subtrees have each at least a fraction of $\alpha$ of the total weight of the subtree.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] There are several self-balanced binary search trees, including T-tree, treap, red-black tree, B-tree, 2–3 tree, and Splay tree.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are used in sorting algorithms such as tree sort, where all the elements are inserted at once and the tree is traversed at an in-order fashion.
[src:avl-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are used in implementing priority queues, using the node's key as priorities.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] In computer science, a **binary tree** is a tree data structure in which each node has at most two children, referred to as the *left child* and the *right child*.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] That is, it is a *k*-ary tree where *k* = 2.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] A recursive definition using set theory is that a binary tree is a triple (*L*, *S*, *R*), where *L* and *R* are binary trees or the empty set and *S* is a singleton (a single–element set) containing the root.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] From a graph theory perspective, binary trees as defined here are arborescences.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] A binary tree may thus be also called a **bifurcating arborescence**, a term which appears in some early programming books before the modern computer science terminology prevailed.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] It is also possible to interpret a binary tree as an undirected, rather than directed graph, in which case a binary tree is an ordered, rooted tree.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Some authors use **rooted binary tree** instead of *binary tree* to emphasize the fact that the tree is rooted, but as defined above, a binary tree is always rooted.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] In mathematics, what is termed *binary tree* can vary significantly from author to author.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Some use the definition commonly used in computer science, but others define it as every non-leaf having exactly two children and don't necessarily label the children as left and right either.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] a binary tree has a root node, which has 0 or 2 children nodes (which in turn may have their 0 or 2 children, and so on).
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] This definition implies two limitations: a full binary tree contains at least one node, and no node can have only one child.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] This is resolved with the next definition.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] The extended tree definition starts with the assumption the tree can be empty.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] To be complete from the graph point of view, both definitions of a tree should be extended by a definition of the corresponding branches sets.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Informally, the branches set can be described as a set of all ordered pairs of nodes (r, s) where r is a root node of any subtree appearing in the definition, and s is a root node of any of its T1 and T2 subtrees (in case the respective subtree is not empty).
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Another way of imagining this construction (and understanding the terminology) is to consider instead of the empty set a different type of node—for instance square nodes if the regular ones are circles.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] A binary tree is a rooted tree that is also an ordered tree (a.k.a. plane tree) in which every node has at most two children.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] A rooted tree naturally imparts a notion of levels (distance from the root); thus, for every node, a notion of children may be defined as the nodes connected to it a level below.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Ordering of these children (e.g., by drawing them on a plane) makes it possible to distinguish a left child from a right child.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] But this still does not distinguish between a node with left but not a right child from a node with right but no left child.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] The necessary distinction can be made by first partitioning the edges; i.e., defining the binary tree as triplet (V, E1, E2), where (V, E1 ∪ E2) is a rooted tree (equivalently arborescence) and E1 ∩ E2 is empty, and also requiring that for all *j* ∈ { 1, 2 }, every node has at most one E*j* child.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] A more informal way of making the distinction is to say, quoting the Encyclopedia of Mathematics, that "every node has a left child, a right child, neither, or both" and to specify that these "are all different" binary trees.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Tree terminology is not well-standardized and therefore may vary among examples in the available literature.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] In combinatorics, one considers the problem of counting the number of full binary trees of a given size.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] The size of the tree is taken to be the number *n* of internal nodes (those with two children); the other nodes are leaf nodes and there are *n* + 1 of them.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] The number of such binary trees of size *n* is equal to the number of ways of fully parenthesizing a string of *n* + 1 symbols (representing leaves) separated by *n* binary operators (representing internal nodes), to determine the argument subexpressions of each operator.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] The correspondence to binary trees should be obvious, and the addition of redundant parentheses (around an already parenthesized expression or around the full expression) is disallowed (or at least not counted as producing a new possibility).
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] There is a unique binary tree of size 0 (consisting of a single leaf), and any other binary tree is characterized by the pair of its left and right children; if these have sizes *i* and *j* respectively, the full tree has size *i* + *j* + 1.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Therefore, the number $C_{n}$ of binary trees of size *n* has the following recursive description $C_{0}=1$ , and $\textstyle C_{n}=\sum _{i=0}^{n-1}C_{i}C_{n-1-i}$ for any positive integer *n*.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] It follows that $C_{n}$ is the Catalan number of index *n*.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] The above parenthesized strings should not be confused with the set of words of length 2*n* in the Dyck language, which consist only of parentheses in such a way that they are properly balanced.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] These Dyck words do not correspond to binary trees in the same way.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Instead, they are related by the following recursively defined bijection: the Dyck word equal to the empty string corresponds to the binary tree of size 0 with only one leaf.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Any other Dyck word can be written as ( $w_{1}$ ) $w_{2}$ , where $w_{1}$ , $w_{2}$ are themselves (possibly empty) Dyck words and where the two written parentheses are matched.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] The bijection is then defined by letting the words $w_{1}$ and $w_{2}$ correspond to the binary trees that are the left and right children of the root.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] The ability to represent binary trees as strings of symbols and parentheses implies that binary trees can represent the elements of a free magma on a singleton set.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Binary trees can be constructed from programming language primitives in several ways.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] In a language with records and references, binary trees are typically constructed by having a tree node structure which contains some data and references to its left child and its right child.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Sometimes it also contains a reference to its unique parent.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] If a node has fewer than two children, some of the child pointers may be set to a special null value, or to a special sentinel node.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] This method of storing binary trees wastes a fair bit of memory, as the pointers will be null (or point to the sentinel) more than half the time; a more conservative representation alternative is threaded binary tree.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] In languages with tagged unions such as ML, a tree node is often a tagged union of two types of nodes, one of which is a 3-tuple of data, left child, and right child, and the other of which is a "leaf" node, which contains no data and functions much like the null value in a language with pointers.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] For example, the following line of code in OCaml (an ML dialect) defines a binary tree that stores a character in each node.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Binary trees can also be stored in breadth-first order as an implicit data structure in arrays, and if the tree is a complete binary tree, this method wastes no space.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] In this compact arrangement, if a node has an index *i*, its children are found at indices $2i+1$ (for the left child) and $2i+2$ (for the right), while its parent (if any) is found at index *$\left\lfloor {\frac {i-1}{2}}\right\rfloor$* (assuming the root has index zero).
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Alternatively, with a 1-indexed array, the implementation is simplified with children found at $2i$ and $2i+1$ , and parent found at $\lfloor i/2\rfloor$ .
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] This method benefits from more compact storage and better locality of reference, particularly during a preorder traversal.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] A succinct data structure is one which occupies close to minimum possible space, as established by information theoretical lower bounds.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] The number of different binary trees on n nodes is $\mathrm {C} _{n}$ , the n th Catalan number (assuming we view trees with identical *structure* as identical).
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] For large n , this is about $4^{n}$ ; thus we need at least about $\log _{2}4^{n}=2n$ bits to encode it.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] A succinct binary tree therefore would occupy 2*n*+o(*n*) bits (with 'o()' being the Little-o notation).
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] One simple representation which meets this bound is to visit the nodes of the tree in preorder, outputting "1" for an internal node and "0" for a leaf.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] If the tree contains data, we can simply simultaneously store it in a consecutive array in preorder.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] The string *structure* has only $2n+1$ bits in the end, where n is the number of (internal) nodes; we don't even have to store its length.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] More sophisticated succinct representations allow not only compact storage of trees but even useful operations on those trees directly while they're still in their succinct form.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] There is a natural one-to-one correspondence between ordered trees and binary trees.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Let *T* be a node of an ordered tree, and let *B* denote *T's* image in the corresponding binary tree.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Then *B's* *left* child represents *T's* first child, while the *B's right* child represents *T'*s next sibling.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] In the pictured binary tree, the black, left, edges represent *first child*, while the blue, right, edges represent *next sibling*.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] This representation is called a left-child right-sibling binary tree.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] There are a variety of different operations that can be performed on binary trees.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Some are mutator operations, while others simply return useful information about the tree.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Nodes can be inserted into binary trees in between two other nodes or added after a leaf node.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] In binary trees, a node that is inserted is specified as to whose child it will be.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] To add a new node after leaf node A, A assigns the new node as one of its children and the new node assigns node A as its parent.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Insertion on internal nodes is slightly more complex than on leaf nodes.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Say that the internal node is node A and that node B is the child of A.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] (If the insertion is to insert a right child, then B is the right child of A, and similarly with a left child insertion.) A assigns its child to the new node and the new node assigns its parent to A.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Then the new node assigns its child to B and B assigns its parent as the new node.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Deletion is the process whereby a node is removed from the tree.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Only certain nodes in a binary tree can be removed unambiguously.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Suppose that the node to delete is node A.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] If A has no children, deletion is accomplished by setting the child of A's parent to null.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] If A has one child, set the parent of A's child to A's parent and set the child of A's parent to A's child.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] In a binary tree, a node with two children cannot be deleted unambiguously.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] However, in certain binary trees (including binary search trees) these nodes *can* be deleted, though with a rearrangement of the tree structure.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Pre-order, in-order, and post-order traversal visit each node in a tree by recursively visiting each node in the left and right subtrees of the root.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Below are the brief descriptions of above mentioned traversals.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] In pre-order, we always visit the current node; next, we recursively traverse the current node's left subtree, and then we recursively traverse the current node's right subtree.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] The pre-order traversal is a topologically sorted one, because a parent node is processed before any of its child nodes is done.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] In in-order, we always recursively traverse the current node's left subtree; next, we visit the current node, and lastly, we recursively traverse the current node's right subtree.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] In post-order, we always recursively traverse the current node's left subtree; next, we recursively traverse the current node's right subtree and then visit the current node.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Post-order traversal can be useful to get postfix expression of a binary expression tree.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] In depth-first order, we always attempt to visit the node farthest from the root node that we can, but with the caveat that it must be a child of a node we have already visited.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Unlike a depth-first search on graphs, there is no need to remember all the nodes we have visited, because a tree cannot contain cycles.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] See depth-first search for more information.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Contrasting with depth-first order is breadth-first order, which always attempts to visit the node closest to the root that it has not already visited.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] See breadth-first search for more information.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] In a complete binary tree, a node's breadth-index (*i* − (2*d* − 1)) can be used as traversal instructions from the root.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] Reading bitwise from left to right, starting at bit *d* − 1, where *d* is the node's distance from the root (*d* = ⌊log2(*i*+1)⌋) and the node in question is not the root itself (*d* > 0).
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] When the breadth-index is masked at bit *d* − 1, the bit values 0 and 1 mean to step either left or right, respectively.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] The process continues by successively checking the next bit to the right until there are no more.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] The rightmost bit indicates the final traversal from the desired node's parent to the node itself.
[src:avl-tree/binary-tree] There is a time-space trade-off between iterating a complete binary tree this way versus each node having pointer(s) to its sibling(s).
[src:avl-tree/order-statistic-tree] Both operations can be performed in *O*(log *n*) worst case time when a self-balancing tree is used as the base data structure.
[src:avl-tree/order-statistic-tree] To turn a regular search tree into an order statistic tree, the nodes of the tree need to store one additional value, which is the size of the subtree rooted at that node (i.e., the number of nodes below it).
[src:avl-tree/order-statistic-tree] Order-statistic trees can be further amended with bookkeeping information to maintain balance (e.g., tree height can be added to get an order statistic AVL tree, or a color bit to get a red–black order statistic tree).
[src:avl-tree/order-statistic-tree] Alternatively, the size field can be used in conjunction with a weight-balancing scheme at no additional storage cost.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] In computer science, a **self-balancing binary search tree** (BST) is any node-based binary search tree that automatically keeps its height (maximal number of levels below the root) small in the face of arbitrary item insertions and deletions.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] These operations when designed for a self-balancing binary search tree, contain precautionary measures against boundlessly increasing tree height, so that these abstract data structures receive the attribute "self-balancing".
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For **height-balanced** binary trees, the height is defined to be logarithmic $O(\log n)$ in the number n of items.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] This is the case for many binary search trees, such as AVL trees and red–black trees.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Splay trees and treaps are self-balancing but not height-balanced, as their height is not guaranteed to be logarithmic in the number of items.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing binary search trees provide efficient implementations for mutable ordered lists, and can be used for other abstract data structures such as associative arrays, priority queues and sets.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Most operations on a binary search tree (BST) take time directly proportional to the height of the tree, so it is desirable to keep the height small.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] In other words, the minimum height of a binary tree with *n* nodes is log2(*n*), rounded down; that is, $\lfloor \log _{2}n\rfloor$ .
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] However, the simplest algorithms for BST item insertion may yield a tree with height *n* in rather common situations.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For example, when the items are inserted in sorted key order, the tree degenerates into a linked list with *n* nodes.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] The difference in performance between the two situations may be enormous: for example, when *n* = 1,000,000, the minimum height is $\lfloor \log _{2}(1,000,000)\rfloor =19$ .
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] If the data items are known ahead of time, the height can be kept small, in the average sense, by adding values in a random order, resulting in a random binary search tree.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] However, there are many situations (such as online algorithms) where this randomization is not viable.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing binary trees solve this problem by performing transformations on the tree (such as tree rotations) at key insertion times, in order to keep the height proportional to log2(*n*).
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Although a certain overhead is involved, it is not bigger than the always necessary lookup cost and may be justified by ensuring fast execution of all operations.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] While it is possible to maintain a BST with minimum height with expected $O(\log n)$ time operations (lookup/insertion/removal), the additional space requirements required to maintain such a structure tend to outweigh the decrease in search time.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For comparison, an AVL tree is guaranteed to be within a factor of 1.44 of the optimal height while requiring only two additional bits of storage in a naive implementation.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Therefore, most self-balancing BST algorithms keep the height within a constant factor of this lower bound.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] In the asymptotic ("Big-O") sense, a self-balancing BST structure containing *n* items allows the lookup, insertion, and removal of an item in $O(\log n)$ worst-case time, and ordered enumeration of all items in $O(n)$ time.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For some implementations these are per-operation time bounds, while for others they are amortized bounds over a sequence of operations.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] These times are asymptotically optimal among all data structures that manipulate the key only through comparisons.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing binary search trees can be used in a natural way to construct and maintain ordered lists, such as priority queues.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] They can also be used for associative arrays; key-value pairs are simply inserted with an ordering based on the key alone.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] In this capacity, self-balancing BSTs have a number of advantages and disadvantages over their main competitor, hash tables.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] One advantage of self-balancing BSTs is that they allow fast (indeed, asymptotically optimal) enumeration of the items *in key order*, which hash tables do not provide.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] One disadvantage is that their lookup algorithms get more complicated when there may be multiple items with the same key.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing BSTs have better worst-case lookup performance than most hash tables ( $O(\log n)$ compared to $O(n)$ ), but have worse average-case performance ( $O(\log n)$ compared to $O(1)$ ).
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing BSTs can be used to implement any algorithm that requires mutable ordered lists, to achieve optimal worst-case asymptotic performance.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For example, if binary tree sort is implemented with a self-balancing BST, we have a very simple-to-describe yet asymptotically optimal $O(n\log n)$ sorting algorithm.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Similarly, many algorithms in computational geometry exploit variations on self-balancing BSTs to solve problems such as the line segment intersection problem and the point location problem efficiently.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] (For average-case performance, however, self-balancing BSTs may be less efficient than other solutions.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] Self-balancing BSTs are flexible data structures, in that it is easy to extend them to efficiently record additional information or perform new operations.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] For example, one can record the number of nodes in each subtree having a certain property, allowing one to count the number of nodes in a certain key range with that property in $O(\log n)$ time.
[src:avl-tree/self-balancing-binary-search-tree] These extensions can be used, for example, to optimize database queries or other list-processing algorithms.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] In discrete mathematics, **tree rotation** is an operation on a binary tree that changes the structure without interfering with the order of the elements.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] A tree rotation moves one node up in the tree and one node down.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] It is used to change the shape of the tree, and in particular to decrease its height by moving smaller subtrees down and larger subtrees up, resulting in improved performance of many tree operations.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] There exists an inconsistency in different descriptions as to the definition of the **direction of rotations**.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] This article takes the approach of the directional movement of the rotating node.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] The right rotation operation as shown in the adjacent image is performed with *Q* as the root and hence is a right rotation on, or rooted at, *Q*.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] This operation results in a rotation of the tree in the clockwise direction.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] The inverse operation is the left rotation, which results in a movement in a counter-clockwise direction (the left rotation shown above is rooted at *P*).
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] The key to understanding how a rotation functions is to understand its constraints.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] In particular the order of the leaves of the tree (when read left to right for example) cannot change (another way to think of it is that the order that the leaves would be visited in an in-order traversal must be the same after the operation as before).
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] Another constraint is the main property of a binary search tree, namely that all nodes in the right subtree are greater than the parent and all nodes in the left subtree are less than the parent.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] Notice that the right child of a left child of the root of a sub-tree (for example node B in the diagram for the tree rooted at Q) can become the left child of the root, that itself becomes the right child of the "new" root in the rotated sub-tree, without violating either of those constraints.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] As seen in the diagram, the order of the leaves doesn't change.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] The opposite operation also preserves the order and is the second kind of rotation.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] Assuming this is a binary search tree, as stated above, the elements must be interpreted as variables that can be compared to each other.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] The alphabetic characters to the left are used as placeholders for these variables.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] In the animation to the right, capital alphabetic characters are used as variable placeholders while lowercase Greek letters are placeholders for an entire set of variables.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] The circles represent individual nodes and the triangles represent subtrees.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] Each subtree could be empty, consist of a single node, or consist of any number of nodes.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] When a subtree is rotated, the subtree side upon which it is rotated increases its height by one node while the other subtree decreases its height.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] This makes tree rotations useful for rebalancing a tree.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] Consider the terminology of **Root** for the parent node of the subtrees to rotate, **Pivot** for the node which will become the new parent node, **RS** for the side of rotation and **OS** for the opposite side of rotation.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] For the root Q in the diagram above, **RS** is C and **OS** is P.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] The programmer must also make sure that the root's parent points to the pivot after the rotation.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] Also, the programmer should note that this operation may result in a new root for the entire tree and take care to update pointers accordingly.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] The tree rotation renders the inorder traversal of the binary tree invariant.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] This implies the order of the elements is not affected when a rotation is performed in any part of the tree.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] Computing one from the other is very simple.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] There are also *double rotations*, which are combinations of left and right rotations.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] A *double left* rotation at X can be defined to be a right rotation at the right child of X followed by a left rotation at X; similarly, a *double right* rotation at X can be defined to be a left rotation at the left child of X followed by a right rotation at X.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] Tree rotations are used in a number of tree data structures such as AVL trees, red–black trees, WAVL trees, splay trees, and treaps.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] They require only constant time because they are *local* transformations: they only operate on 5 nodes, and need not examine the rest of the tree.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] A tree can be rebalanced using rotations.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] After a rotation, the side of the rotation increases its height by 1 whilst the side opposite the rotation decreases its height similarly.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] Therefore, one can strategically apply rotations to nodes whose left child and right child differ in height by more than 1.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] Self-balancing binary search trees apply this operation automatically.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] A type of tree which uses this rebalancing technique is the AVL tree.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] Can the rotation distance between two binary trees be computed in polynomial time?
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] The rotation distance between any two binary trees with the same number of nodes is the minimum number of rotations needed to transform one into the other.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] With this distance, the set of *n*-node binary trees becomes a metric space: the distance is symmetric, positive when given two different trees, and satisfies the triangle inequality.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] It is an open problem whether there exists a polynomial time algorithm for calculating rotation distance, though several variants of the rotation distance problem admit polynomial time algorithms.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] Daniel Sleator, Robert Tarjan and William Thurston showed that the rotation distance between any two *n*-node trees (for *n* ≥ 11) is at most 2*n* − 6, and that some pairs of trees are this far apart as soon as *n* is sufficiently large.
[src:avl-tree/tree-rotation] Lionel Pournin showed that, in fact, such pairs exist whenever *n* ≥ 11.
